  <fr:p>We show the result for monos: let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C\xrightarrow {F} D]]></fr:tex> be faithful and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Fx\xrightarrow {Ff}   Fy]]></fr:tex> a mono in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. Then given <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\overset {g,h}{\rightrightarrows } x]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[fg = fh]]></fr:tex>,
  we have by functoriality that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[FfFg = FfFh]]></fr:tex>, so since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Ff]]></fr:tex> is a mono, we
  have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Fg = Fh]]></fr:tex>. Now by faithfulness of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g = h]]></fr:tex>, as desired.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>To conclude for epis, note that the opposite functor
  <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C^\text {op}\xrightarrow {F^\text {op}}D^\text {op}]]></fr:tex> remains faithful, so the result for monos
  <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-0009.xml"
addr="rs-0009"
title="Categorical duality">dualizes</fr:link>.</fr:p>
